definition.value: Any monocyclic heteroarene consisting of a five-membered ring containing nitrogen. Azoles can also contain one or more other non-carbon atoms, such as nitrogen, sulfur or oxygen.
Any substance that induces the process of apoptosis (programmed cell death) in multi-celled organisms.
A hormone agonist that binds to and activates progesterone receptors.
An EC 5.99.1.* (miscellaneous isomerase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any of the topoisomerases (enzymes that regulate the overwinding or underwinding of DNA).
Any protein kinase inhibitor that inhibits the action of an Aurora kinase (a group of serine/threonine kinases that are essential for cell proliferation).
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the amino groups of any alkane-alpha,omega-diamine; major species at pH 7.3.
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of a transferase (EC 2.*)

An organophosphate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of N-monoacetylchitobiose-6-phosphate, obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups and protonation of the free amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A disaccharide phosphate that is N'-monoacetylchitobiose substituted at position 6' by a phospho group.

A signalling molecule produced and used by bacteria participating in quorum sensing, that is, in cell-cell communication to coordinate community-wide regulation of processes such as biofilm formation, virulence, and bioluminescence in populations of bacteria. Such communication can occur both within and between different species of bacteria.
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of novobiocin.
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the 5-hydroxy group to the tertiary amino group of rifampicin.
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of tetracycline obtained by deprotonation of the two enolic hydroxy groups and protonation of the tertiary amino group.
An amino-acid anion in which the amino group is situated gamma- to the carboxylate group.
A carbohydrate acid anion obtained by deprotonation of any aldonic acid. Major structure at pH 7.3 of aldonate compounds.

An organophosphate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of D-galactosamine 6-phosphate, obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups and protonation of the 2-amino group. Major structure at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of an aldehydic acid.
Any organooxygen compound that has the general formula RC(OR(1))(OR(2))(OR(3)), where R(1), R(2), R(3) =/= H.

Any organic molecular entity whose stucture is based on derivatives of a phenyl-substituted 1-phenylpropane possessing a C15 or C16 skeleton, or such a structure which is condensed with a C6-C3 lignan precursors. The term is a 'superclass' comprising all members of the classes of flavonoid, isoflavonoid, neoflavonoid, chalcones, dihydrochalcones, aurones, pterocarpan, coumestans, rotenoid, flavonolignan, homoflavonoid and flavonoid oligomers. Originally restricted to natural products, the term is also applied to synthetic compounds related to them.
Any organic molecular entity derived from a natural product by partial chemical synthesis.
Any molecule that consists of at least one carbon atom as part of the electrically neutral entity.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the primary amino groups of kanamycin C.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the primary amino groups of kanamycin X.
A kanamycin that is kanamycin A in which the 6'-amino group is replaced by a hydroxy group.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the primary amino groups of kanamycin D.
A kanamycin that is kanamycin A in which the 3''-amino group is replaced by a hydroxy group.
An  EC 1.11.1.* (peroxidases) inhibitor that inhibits the action of L-ascorbate peroxidase (EC 1.11.1.11).

label.value: EC 3.6.* (hydrolases acting on acid anhydrides) inhibitor

definition.value: Any hydrolase inhibitor that interferes with the action of a hydrolase which acts on acid anhydrides (EC 3.6.*.*).
Any compound that inhibits oxidative phosphorylation.
An agonist at any adenosine receptor.
A drug used in treating and healing of wounds.
Any organic molecule containing a C#C bond.
Any naphthyridine derivative that is a derivative of 1,8-naphthyridine.
Any organonitrogen heterocyclic compound that is a derivative of a naphthyridine.
An L-alpha-amino acid which is biosynthesised from erythrose 4-phosphate and phosphoenolpyruvate (i.e. phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan). A closed class.

A carbonyl compound produced as a water-soluble byproduct when fatty acids are broken down for energy in the liver. There are three endogenous ketone bodies: acetone, acetoacetic acid, and (R)-3-hydroxybutyric acid; others may be produced as a result of the metabolism of synthetic triglycerides.
A carbohydrate derivative in which one or more of the oxygens or hydroxy groups of the parent carbohydrate is replaced by sulfur or -SR, where R can be hydrogen or any group.
An  EC 1.17.* (oxidoreductase acting on CH or CH2) inhibitor that inhibits the action of ribonucleoside-diphosphate reductase (EC 1.17.4.1).
An optically active form of glyceric acid having L-configuration.
A D-alpha-amino acid zwitterion that is D-asparagine in which a proton has been transferred from the carboxy group to the amino group. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
An imidazolidinone that is imidazolin-2-one substituted at positions 4 and 5 by hydroxy and ureido groups respectively.
A role borne by a molecule that acts to counteract or neutralize the deleterious effects of paracetamol (acetaminophen).
An acridinium ion resulting from the protonation of the endocyclic nitrogen of 3,6-diaminoacridine.
An acridinium ion resulting from the protonation of the endocyclic nitrogen and one of the amino groups of 3,6-diaminoacridine.
A compound that causes the contraction of body tissues, typically used to reduce bleeding from minor abrasions.
A pentahydroxyflavone that is 7-hydroxyflavonol bearing three additional hydroxy substituents at positions 2' 4' and 5.
An inorganic sodium salt having molybdate as the counterion.
An EC 1.11.* (oxidoreductase acting on peroxide as donors) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any of the peroxidases (EC 1.11.1.*).

label.value: EC 6.1.1.* (ligases forming aminoacyl tRNA and related compounds) inhibitor

definition.value: An EC 6.1.* (C-O bond-forming ligase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any ligase forming aminoacyl tRNA and related compounds (EC 6.1.1.*).
